{
  format: 1
  name: json-null-ranks-first-optional-none-ranks-last
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.3", "§A.1", "§A.7"]
  tags: ["ordering", "json", "optional"]
  note: '''
    Attack: conflate JSON `null` with Liasse `none`. They are different values
    (A.1: "JSON null is a value of json; none is absence"; §7.3: "none remains
    distinct from JSON null") and they sort at OPPOSITE ends.

    Field type is `json?`. §B.3 gives the intra-json rank
      null < bool < number < string < array < object
    and the optional wrapper (§B.2 as restated in §B.3 for json?) is
      ASC:  null ... object, none
    So ascending yields: JSON null FIRST (lowest json rank), then bool, number,
    string, array, object, and finally the none row (absent value) LAST.

    A runtime that treats JSON null and none as the same sentinel would collapse
    the first and last rows together — the exact bug this case is built to catch.
    The none row is seeded by omitting the optional field (A.1); the JSON-null
    row is seeded with an explicit `j: null`.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.jsonrank@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      docs: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        j: "json?"
      }
      $public: {
        by_j: { $view: ".docs { id, j, $sort: [j, id] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      docs: {
        r_obj: { j: {} }
        r_none: {}
        r_num: { j: 42 }
        r_null: { j: null }
        r_arr: { j: [1] }
        r_bool: { j: false }
        r_str: { j: "x" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_j", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "r_null", j: null }
        { id: "r_bool", j: false }
        { id: "r_num", j: 42 }
        { id: "r_str", j: "x" }
        { id: "r_arr", j: [1] }
        { id: "r_obj", j: {} }
        { id: "r_none" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
